page.text:
==English==
            ===Etymology===
            From {{inh|en|enm|*amasen||to bewilder, perplex}}, from {{inh|en|ang|āmasian||to confuse, astonish}}, from
            {{m|ang|ā-|pos=perfective prefix}} + {{m|ang|*masian||to confound}}, equivalent to {{prefix|en|a|maze}}.
            ===Pronunciation===
            * {{a|UK}} {{IPA|en|/əˈmeɪz/}}
            * {{audio|en|En-us-amaze.ogg|Audio (US)}}
            * {{rhymes|en|eɪz|s=2}}
            ===Verb===
            {{en-verb}}
            # {{lb|en|transitive}} To fill with wonder and surprise; to [[astonish]], [[astound]], [[surprise]] or
            [[perplex]]. {{defdate|from 16th c.}}
            #: {{ux|en|He was '''amazed''' when he found that the girl was a robot.}}
            #* {{RQ:KJV|Matthew|12|23|passage=And all the people were '''amazed''', and said, Is not this the son of
            David?}}
            #* '''1759''', {{w|Oliver Goldsmith}}, ''The Present State of Polite Learning''
            #*: Spain has long fallen from '''amazing''' Europe with her wit, to amusing them with the greatness of her
            Catholic credulity.
            # {{lb|en|intransitive}} To undergo amazement; to be astounded.
            #*{{quote-book|en|1890|{{w|Bayard Taylor}}|Faust: A Tragedy|passage=Eye is blinded, ear '''amazes'''.}}
            # {{lb|en|obsolete}} To [[stupefy]]; to knock unconscious. {{defdate|13th|17th c.}}
            # {{lb|en|obsolete}} To bewilder; to stupefy; to bring into a maze.
            #* {{RQ:Shakespeare Venus and Adonis|passage=a labyrinth to '''amaze''' his foes}}
            # {{lb|en|obsolete}} To [[terrify]], to fill with [[panic]]. {{defdate|16th|18th c.}}
            #* {{RQ:Burton Melancholy}}, New York Review Books 2001, p.261:
            #*: [Fear] '''amazeth''' many men that are to speak or show themselves in public assemblies, or before some
            great personages {{...}}
            ====Related terms====
            * {{l|en|amazing}}
            * {{l|en|amazement}}
            ====Translations====
            {{trans-top|to fill with surprise, astonish}}
            * Arabic: {{t|ar|عَجَّبَ}}
            * Assyrian Neo-Aramaic: {{t|aii|ܥܲܓ̰ܸܒ|tr=ʿājib}}
            * Bulgarian: {{t+|bg|смайвам}}, {{t+|bg|слисвам}}, {{t+|bg|удивлявам}}, {{t+|bg|изумявам}}
            * Czech: {{t+|cs|ohromit}}, {{t|cs|udivit}}
            * Finnish: {{t+|fi|hämmästyttää}}
            * French: {{t+|fr|stupéfier}}
            * Georgian: {{t|ka|გაოცება|sc=Geor}}
            * German: {{t+|de|verwundern}}
            * Greek: {{t+|el|καταπλήσσω|sc=Grek}}, {{t+|el|εκπλήσσω|sc=Grek}}
            * Hebrew: {{t|he|הדהים|tr=hidhím}}
            {{trans-mid}}
            * Hungarian: {{t+|hu|elképeszt}}
            * Japanese: {{t+|ja|驚かす|tr=odorokasu}}
            * Ladino: {{t|lad|asolombrar}}
            * Polish: {{t+|pl|zdumiewać|impf}}, {{t+|pl|zdumieć|pf}}, {{t|pl|osłupić|pf}}, {{t+|pl|zadziwiać|impf}},
            {{t+|pl|zadziwić|pf}}
            * Portuguese: {{t+|pt|espantar}}, {{t+|pt|surpreender}}
            * Romanian: {{t+|ro|uimi}}, {{t+|ro|minuna}}
            * Russian: {{t+|ru|изумля́ть|impf}}, {{t+|ru|изуми́ть|pf}}
            * Slovene: {{t|sl|osupiti}}, {{t|sl|presuniti}}
            * Spanish: {{t+|es|pasmar}}, {{t+|es|sorprender}}, {{t+|es|asombrar}}
            * Turkish: {{t+|tr|şaşırtmak}}
            * Volapük: {{t+|vo|stunükön}}
            {{trans-bottom}}
            ===Noun===
            {{en-noun|-}}
            # {{lb|en|now|_|poetic}} [[amazement|Amazement]], [[astonishment]]. {{defdate|from 16th c.}}
            #* {{RQ:Spenser Faerie Queene|passage=All in '''amaze''' he suddenly vp start / With sword in hand, and with
            the old man went [...].|1|2}}
            #* {{quote-book|1=en|year=1887|author=H. Rider Haggard|authorlink=H. Rider Haggard|title=She: A History of
            Adventure|url=http://www.gutenberg.org/files/3155/3155-0.txt|passage=Presently, however, as we stood in
            '''amaze''', gazing at the marvellous sight, and wondering whence the rosy radiance flowed, a dread and
            beautiful thing happened.}}
            #* '''1891''', {{w|Mary Noailles Murfree}}, ''In the "Stranger People's" Country'', Nebraska 2005,
            p. 103:
            #*: Shattuck looked at him in '''amaze'''.
            #* '''1985''', {{w|Lawrence Durrell}}, ''Quinx'', Faber & Faber 2004 (''Avignon Quintet''), p. 1361:
            #*: She took the proffered cheque and stared at it with puzzled '''amaze''', dazed by her own behaviour.
