            ===Conjunction===
            {{en-con}}
            # {{lb|en|literary|archaic}} [[because|Because]], [[as]], [[since]].
            #: {{ux|en|I had to stay with my wicked stepmother, '''for''' I had nowhere else to go.}}
            #* {{quote-book|en|year=c. 1601|authorlink=William
            Shakespeare|first=William|last=Shakespeare|title={{w|Twelfth Night}}|others=act 3, scene
            4|url=http://www.opensourceshakespeare.org/views/plays/playmenu.php?WorkID=12night|passage={{...}}Dismount
            thy tuck, be yare in thy preparation, '''for''' thy assailant is quick, skillful and deadly.}}
            #* {{quote-book|en|year=1885|authorlink=Richard Francis Burton|first=Richard
            Francis|last=Burton|title={{w|The Book of the Thousand Nights and a Night}}|passage={{...}}nor is there
            found, in sea or on land, a sweeter or pleasanter of gifts than she; '''for''' she is prime in comeliness
            and seemlihead of face and symmetrical shape of perfect grace; her check is ruddy dight, her brow flower
            white, her teeth gem-bright, her eyes blackest black and whitest white, her hips of heavy weight, her waist
            slight and her favour exquisite.}}
            #* {{quote-book|en|year=1900|authorlink=L. Frank Baum|first=L[yman] Frank|last=Baum|title={{w|The Wonderful
            Wizard of Oz}}|chapter=23|passage="By means of the Golden Cap I shall command the Winged Monkeys to
            carry you to the gates of the Emerald City," said Glinda, "'''for''' it would be a shame to
            deprive the people of so wonderful a ruler."}}
            ====Synonyms====
            * {{l|en|given that}}, {{l|en|seeing that}}; see also [[Thesaurus:because]]
