            ===Preposition===
            {{en-prep}}
            # [[towards|Towards]]; in the [[direction]] of.
            #: {{ux|en|The astronauts headed '''for''' the moon.}}
            #: {{ux|en|Run [[for]] the hills!}}
            #: {{ux|en|He was headed '''for''' the door when he remembered.}}
            #* {{RQ:Bacon New Atlantis|page=1|passage=Wee ſailed from ''Peru'', (where wee had continued by the ſpace of
            one whole yeare,) '''for''' ''China'' and ''Iapan'', by the South Sea; [...]}}
            # Directed at; [[intended]] to [[belong]] to.
            #: {{ux|en|I have something '''for''' you.}}
            # In order to help, benefit, gratify, honor etc. (someone or something).
            #: {{ux|en|Everything I do, I do '''for''' you.}}
            #: {{ux|en|We're having a birthday party '''for''' Janet.}}
            #: {{ux|en|The mayor gave a speech '''for''' the charity gala.}}
            #* {{quote-song|en|year=1976|author={{w|Michael McDonald (musician)|Michael McDonald}}|artist={{w|The Doobie
            Brothers}}|title={{w|Takin' It to the Streets (song)|Takin' It to the Streets}}|passage=You, telling me the
            things you're gonna do '''for''' me.}}
            # To be used or treated in a stated way, or with a stated purpose.
            #: {{ux|en|This is a new bell '''for''' my bicycle.}}
            #: {{ux|en|The cake is '''for''' Tom and Helen's anniversary.}}
            #: {{ux|en|These apples here are '''for''' eating. The rest are '''for''' throwing away.}}
            # [[support|Supporting]], in [[favour]] of.
            #: {{ant|en|against}}
            #: {{ux|en|All those '''for''' the motion, raise your hands.
            }}
            #: {{ux|en|Who's '''for''' ice-cream?}}
            #: {{ux|en|I'm '''for''' going by train}}
            #: {{ux|en|Ten voted '''for''', and three against.|q=with implied object}}
            # [[because of|Because of]].
            #: {{ux|en|He wouldn't apologize; and just '''for''' that, she refused to help him.}}
            #: {{ux|en|He looks better '''for''' having lost weight.|q=UK usage}}
            #: {{ux|en|She was the worse '''for''' drink.}}
            #: {{ux|en|I like her '''for''' lots of reasons.}}
            #* {{RQ:Shakespeare Henry 6-3|II|v|passage=with fiery eyes sparkling '''for''' very wrath}}
            #* {{quote-book|en|year=1867|author=Frederick Metcalfe|title=The Oxonian in Iceland|page=202|passage="A
            summerly day for you," said my host; "You ought to be here in winter. It is impossible then to get
            out of the doors '''for''' the snow and wind. Ugh! dreadful weather!"}}
            #* '''1864''', George Etell Sargent, ''The Story of a City Arab'' (page 313)
            #*: I could not see his hands, '''for''' the thick gloves he wore, and his face was partially concealed by a
            red woollen comforter; but his entire appearance and manners tallied with what I had seen of Yorkshire
            farmerhood.
            # [[intend|Intended]] to [[cure]], [[remove]] or [[counteract]]; [[in order to]] cure, remove or counteract.
            #: {{ux|en|This medicine is '''for''' your cough.}}
            #: {{ux|en|I need to spray my house '''for''' termites.}}
            # Over (a period of time).
            #: {{ux|en|I've lived here '''for''' three years.}}
            #: {{ux|en|They fought '''for''' days over a silly pencil.}}
            #* {{RQ:Addison Meta}}
            #*: To guide the sun's bright chariot '''for''' a day.
            # Throughout or across (a distance in space).
            #: {{ux|en|I can see '''for''' miles.}}
            #* {{RQ:Shakespeare King Lear|II|iv|passage='''For''' many miles about / There's scarce a bush.}}
            # {{n-g|Used to introduce a subject within a [[to-infinitive]] clause.}}
            #: {{ux|en|It is unreasonable '''for''' our boss to withhold our wages.}}
            #: {{ux|en|All I want is '''for''' you to be happy.}}
            # On behalf of.
            #: {{ux|en|I will stand in '''for''' him.}}
            #: {{ux|en|I speak '''for''' the Prime Minister.}}
            # In the role or capacity of; instead of; in place of.
            #: {{ux|en|I used a hay bale '''for''' a bed.}}
            #: {{ux|en|He's got a turnip '''for''' a brain.}}
            # In exchange for; in correspondence or equivalence with.
            #: {{ux|en|I got five hundred pounds '''for''' that old car!}}
            #: {{ux|en|He matched me blow '''for''' blow.}}
            #* {{RQ:King James Version|Exodus|21|23-24|passage=And if any mischief follow, then thou shalt give life
            '''for''' life, eye '''for''' eye, tooth '''for''' tooth, hand '''for''' hand, foot '''for''' foot.}}
            # In order to [[obtain]] or [[acquire]].
            #: {{ux|en|I am aiming '''for''' completion by the end of business Thursday.}}
            #: {{ux|en|He's going '''for''' his doctorate.}}
            #: {{ux|en|Do you want to go '''for''' coffee?}}
            #: {{ux|en|People all over Greece looked to Delphi '''for''' answers.}}
            #: {{ux|en|Can you go to the store '''for''' some eggs?}}
            #: {{ux|en|I'm saving up '''for''' a car.}}
            #: {{ux|en|Don't wait '''for''' an answer.}}
            #: {{ux|en|What did he ask you '''for'''?}}
            #* {{RQ:Denham Sophy|chapter=Prologue|passage=For we would have you know it, / The loſs will fall on us, not
            on the Poet: / For he writes not '''for''' money, nor '''for''' praiſe, / Nor to be call'd a Wit, nor to
            wear Bayes: {{...}}}}
            # By the [[standard]]s of, usually with the implication that those standards are lower than one might
            otherwise expect.
            #: {{ux|en|Fair '''for''' its day.}}
            #: {{ux|en|She's spry '''for''' an old lady.}}
            # To [[be]], or [[as]] being.
            #: {{ux|en|Don't take me '''for''' a fool.}}
            #* '''17th century''' {{w|Abraham Cowley}}, ''[[s:Of Wit|Of Wit]]''
            #*: We take a falling meteor '''for''' a star.
            #* {{RQ:Locke Conduct}}
            #*: if a man can be persuaded and fully assured of anything '''for''' a truth without having examined, what
            is there that he may not embrace for truth ?
            #* '''c. 1690''', {{w|John Dryden}}, ''Translations'' (Preface)
            #*: Most of our ingenious young men take up some cry'd-up English poet '''for''' their model.
            #* '''1712''', {{w|Ambrose Philips}}, ''The Distrest Mother''
            #*: But let her go '''for''' an ungrateful woman.
            #* '''1976''', {{w|Louis L’Amour}}, ''The Rider of Lost Creek'', Bantam Dell ({{ISBN|978-0-553-89964-1}}),
            Chapter 2:
            #*: They knew him '''for''' a stranger.
            # {{lb|en|usually in the phrase '[[for all]]'}} [[despite|Despite]], [[in spite of]].
            #: {{ux|en|'''For''' all his expensive education, he didn't seem very bright.}}
            #* {{quote-book|1=en|year=1898|author=H.G. Wells|authorlink=H.G. Wells|title={{w|The War of the
            Worlds}}|publisher=William Heinemann|location=London|page=113|passage="You must keep your head. There
            is still hope." "Hope!" "Yes; plentiful hope -- '''for''' all this destruction!"}}
            #* '''1892''' August 6, "The Unbidden Guest", in {{w|Charles Dickens, Jr.}} (editor), ''{{w|All
            the Year Round}}'',<sup >[http://books.google.com/books?id=XNwRAAAAYAAJ ]</sup>
            [http://books.google.com/books?id=XNwRAAAAYAAJ&amp;pg=PA133&amp;dq=%22but+for%22 page 133],
            #*: Mr. Joseph Blenkinshaw was perhaps not worth quite so much as was reported; but '''for''' all that he
            was a very wealthy man {{...}}
            #* {{quote-book|en|year=1968|author=J. J. Scarisbrick|title=Henry VIII|page=240|passage='''For''' all his
            faults, there had been something lofty and great about him - as a judge, as a patron of education, as a
            builder, as an international figure.}}
            # {{senseid|en|desired}} {{n-g|Indicating something desired or anticipated.}}
            #: {{ux|en|O '''for''' the wings of a dove.}}
            #: {{ux|en|Ah! '''for''' wings to soar&nbsp;…}}
            #: {{ux|en|And now '''for''' a slap-up meal!}}
            #* {{RQ:Shakespeare Henry 5|Prologue|text=O '''For''' a Muſe of Fire, that would aſcend / The brighteſt
            Heauen of Inuention :}}
            #* '''1858''' March 27, "The Lay of the Brief", in ''Punch, Or, The London Charivari'', page 129:
            #*: Oh! but to breathe the air / By their side under summer skies! To watch the blush on their cheeks, / The
            light in their liquid eyes. / Oh! but '''for''' one short hour, / To whisper a word of love; {{...}}
            # {{lb|en|in expressions such as '[[for a start]]'}} {{n-g|Introducing the first item(s) in a potential
            sequence.}}
            #: {{ux|en|Go scuba diving? '''For''' one thing, I can't even swim.}}
            # {{lb|en|with names|chiefly|US}} In [[honor]] of; after.
            #: {{ux|en|He is named '''for''' his grandfather.}}
            # Due or facing (a certain outcome or fate).
            #: {{ux|en|He totally screwed up that project. Now he's surely '''for''' the sack.}}
            # {{lb|en|chiefly|US}} [[out of|Out of]]; {{non-gloss definition|used to indicate a fraction, a ratio}}
            #: {{ux|en|In term of base hits, Jones was three '''for''' four on the day}}
            # {{lb|en|cricket}} {{non-gloss definition|Used as part of a score to indicate the number of wickets that
            have fallen.}}
            #: {{ux|en|At close of play, England were 305 '''for''' 3.}}
            # {{lb|en|obsolete}} {{n-g|Indicating that in prevention of which, or through fear of which, anything is
            done.}}
            #* {{RQ:Beaumont Fletcher Comedies and Tragedies|title=The Captain|act=III|scene=v|passage=We'll have a bib,
            '''for''' spoiling of thy doublet.}}
            # {{n-g|Used in various more-or-less idiomatic ways to construe individual verbs, indicating various
            semantic relationships such as target, purpose, result, etc.; see also the entries for individual phrasal
            verbs, e.g. [[ask for]], [[look for]], [[stand for]], etc.}}
            #: {{ux|en|to account '''for''' one's whereabouts&emsp;&emsp;&emsp; to care '''for''' a
            relative&emsp;&emsp;&emsp; to settle '''for''' second best&emsp;&emsp;&emsp; to
            allow '''for''' mistakes}}
            # {{lb|en|nonstandard}} [[So]] ([[that]]), [[in order to]]
            #: {{uxi|en|He took the swing shift [[for]] he could get more overtime.}}
